{"metadata":{"title":"About the Language Reference"},"abstract":[{"text":"Read the notation that the formal grammar uses.","type":"text"}],"sections":[],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This part of the book describes the formal grammar of the Swift programming language."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"The grammar described here is intended to help you understand the language in more","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"detail, rather than to allow you to directly implement a parser or compiler.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Swift language is relatively small, because many common types, functions, and operators"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"that appear virtually everywhere in Swift code"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"are actually defined in the Swift standard library. Although these types, functions,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and operators aren’t part of the Swift language itself,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"they’re used extensively in the discussions and code examples in this part of the book."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":2,"anchor":"How-to-Read-the-Grammar","type":"heading","text":"How to Read the Grammar"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The notation used to describe the formal grammar of the Swift programming language"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"follows a few conventions:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"An arrow (→) is used to mark grammar productions and can be read as “can consist of.”"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Syntactic categories are indicated by "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"italic","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" text and appear on both sides"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"of a grammar production rule.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Literal words and punctuation are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"boldface constant width"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" text","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"and appear only on the right-hand side of a grammar production rule.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Alternative grammar productions are separated by vertical"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"bars (|). When alternative productions are too long to read easily,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"they’re broken into multiple grammar production rules on new lines."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In a few cases, regular font text is used to describe the right-hand side","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Optional syntactic categories and literals are marked by a trailing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"question mark, "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As an example, the grammar of a getter-setter block is defined as follows:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"style":"note","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":""}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}]},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]},{"type":"text","text":" | "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"strong"}]}],"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This definition indicates that a getter-setter block can consist of a getter clause","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"followed by an optional setter clause, enclosed in braces,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"or"}]},{"type":"text","text":" a setter clause followed by a getter clause, enclosed in braces."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The grammar production above is equivalent to the following two productions,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"where the alternatives are spelled out explicitly:","type":"text"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":""}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}]},{"text":" → ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"st